Let $n = 2, m = 1, c_1 = 10, v_1(x) = 100 \cdot \mathbb{1}_{x_1 \geq 1}, v_2(x) = 9 x_1 + \frac{2}{3}$. Here, the unique efficient allocation would assign 1 item to bidder 1 and the remaining 9 items to bidder 2, resulting in an SCW of $v_1 (1) + v_2(9) = 100 + 9 \cdot 9 + \frac{2}{3} = 184.\bar{6}$. However, there is no DQ $p \in \mathbb{R}_+$ that bidder 2 would answer with $x_2(p) = (9)$:
$\bullet$ If the price $p$ is below $\frac{9}{10}$, bidder 2 will answer with $x_2(p) = (10)$;
$\bullet$ if the price $p = \frac{9}{10}$, bidder 2 will answer with either $x_2(p) = (10)$ or $x_2(p) = (0)$;
$\bullet$ if the price $p$ is higher than $\frac{9}{10}$, bidder 2 will answer with $x_2(p) = (0)$.
Therefore, the WDP cannot assign 9 items to bidder 2 if only DQs were asked no matter how many DQs were asked. Raising the bids for those bundles would also not help, because this would still not give us any value for 9 items for bidder 2. The best SCW that such WDPs based on DQ responses (and raised DQ responses) can achieve is thus 100, which results in an efficiency of $\frac{100}{184.\bar{6}} \approx 54.28\%$.
Thus, every method that only asks DQs (e.g., CCA or ) will result in inefficient allocations even in the limit of infinitely many iterations in the case of certain value functions (even if raised clock bids are added in the supplementary round).
